description.plain: TTNG (formerly This Town Needs Guns) is a British math rock band from Oxford active since 2004. The name was originally an ironic statement because Oxford has a very miniscule rate of gun ownership. Once they became famous and this irony was not accessible to people, they decided to change their name to simply TTNG.

songs.title: Gibbon

description.plain:
Gibbon is a fan-favorite from TTNG’s full-length album, Animals. The song still finds itself in rotation for the band’s set lists for live performances.

The song speaks of a relationship that has seen its share of time, including ups and downs, and at some point before it was written – it seems that relationship ended. The writer is reflecting on that, and the time they spent together. He concludes that his only regret was not speaking his mind.

songs.lyrics:
Once more in to breaches I cannot gap
One more chance to second guess your thoughts
My friends said that you would be a tough nut to crack
Come back, let's settle this up…

…and down my spine
The faint tingle keeps me up at night
So while you dream I lie awake and look to the stars
No answers forthcoming I find myself locked in your arms

Once more in to breaches I cannot gap
One more chance to second guess your thoughts
My friends said that you would be a tough nut to crack
Come back let's settle this up

Like earth and dust
We’re one and the same; insignificant
Well who am I to presume that we were all but gone?
Perpetually complexing the simple. I for one am done

You brought this on yourself
Our problems had enough time on the shelf
We made the same mistakes
We lived our lives without the give and the take

Are the thoughts that went left unsaid2EmbedShare URLCopyEmbedCopy

songs.title: Baboon

description.plain:
A song about enjoying the intimate moments with a cheating spouse; denying reality and pretending it’s not over for a short time.

In keeping with the math rock tradition of using unusual time signatures, most of the song is in in 23/4, with a few parts in the common 4/4.

What was in your head

“until death”?
The marks upon your skin
Tell tales while envy
Mocks without remorse
And ties you up in knots
One touch and I am in
A trance like state
Entwining our fates to another
The cost of our will now both bound to each other
What was in your head

“until death”?

Your lies unfold
Like lines that were left

songs.lyrics:
I’m in love

Are the 3 words I hope to hear next year
Another place another time another twinkle in eyes caught between awkward glances
In crowded social scenes, another breeding ground for apathy
To tire me into indifference

Now that I’m numb
To places I had run from
Know when you’re wrong
It’s cause you’re fallible, just like everyone

Sentenced to an evening as the party entertainment’s prop
Oh but it’s only you that I am thinking of

So hard to take that I might break

If time has taught us this much
It’s that honesty is the cornerstone of trust

Waiting for endings of evenings that never seem to stop. Enough
In short I’ve come
Back to the places I had run from
You saw it all

songs.title: Cat Fantastic

description.plain: Possibly anti-capitalistic, this song talks about the apathy we have for each other as a class-divided society.

songs.embed_content: Read “Cat Fantastic” by TTNG on Genius

body.plain: Possibly anti-capitalistic, this song talks about the apathy we have for each other as a class-divided society.

songs.lyrics:
[Verse 1]
Red wine and tan lines
Colour our differences
You feel less satisfied
The more that you acquire
Black cabs and bar tabs
To help you get away
And you feel quite justified
To feed your magpie's eyes

[Hook]
You'll be happy
When you're willing
To share

[Verse 2]
Worn holes in old clothes
Wait for the hand-me-downs
Tethered, tangled, and tied;
The suit that fits too tight
Hide behind the bread line
Hunger howls our pockets dry
And it should cripple your pride
To know others won't survive
[Hook]
We'll be happy
When we're willing
To share

[Bridge]
Gather the right minds
And slowly through time
All the right minds
Ignoring patience that we lack
Will inform the new minds
And likely inclined all the new minds
Will in turn replace the old

[Outro]
We will change you easily
Great ideals will be replaced

Red wine and tan lines
Colour our differences
Economic divide
This doesn't suit me fineEmbedShare URLCopyEmbedCopy

songs.title: Pig

description.plain:
This song is about a broken relationship that can’t move forward because the other person is addicted to a drug.

Rather than abandon the relationship or try to change his lover, the speaker looks forward to their lover’s next comedown, experiencing them only when they are off their cycle of drug use.

songs.lyrics:

I’ll wait

I'll wait
For you to come back home
Forget about all that keeps me from you
This house built from bricks and stone
Stands as a monument to the lies we told

How did we get so tired

By the unconceived
How bleak

Oh well
Decorate floors with fabric
Dug too deep to break a habit

I’m just fine
Most the time
I’ll get by

songs.title: Consoling Ghosts
songs.embed_content: Read “Consoling Ghosts” by TTNG on Genius
songs.lyrics:
I want to write
But don’t quite know why
What would I read if she replied?
Would she confide
“Had it not been for my suicide
I’d be happy I'm alive, and in my life"
Meet me behind closed eyes
Guilt trip unstitch habit
The planned pattens of blankets you knit
Doomly looming a net
From the catch of attachment you protect
Unfurl this thread

A permanent result
For a temporary fault
I’m left haunted by the thought of your remorse
Sometimes at night between the creased sheets of my mind

Neuron pathways will trace
My memories of the features of her face
In it I’ll place her voice
To offer these words to her English boy
“Your misery is a choice”
Sometimes at night between the creased sheets of my mind
The dead come back to life
And provide advice
Consoling ghosts
Your dreams are the needed host
To talk to those who were once close

songs.lyrics:

A wood box held aloft
Those guys must be so strong
J's voice sounding so grave

"He's gone"

Tie your conscience down
With heavy heads and frowns

Running up the walls
Sick, stressed and all regretful
Of what life could have been
Tired, stretched and thin
Keep it in

You're rolling off the rails
Lights signal fails, amber's tail
Of compensation claims
Screeching brakes and loud crashing sounds

It's over now
Tie your conscience down
With heavy heads and frowns
Our friends all dressed so smartly
This feels oddly, so wrong
A wood box held aloft
Those guys must be so strong
J's voice sounding so grave
Tells me out straight
"He's gone"

But he's helped shape the man that I am nowEmbedShare URLCopyEmbedCopy

songs.title: Coconut Crab

description.plain:
This song is about writing lyrics to songs as stated by lines “just simply paraphrase
all that you’re feeling”, “over melodies”. In the first verse he talks about how easy it seems to write until you actually start doing it. He’s trying to get himself to start.

Now that he’s started, his writing seems mediocre even to himself then he gets frustrated as he can’t come up with anything “good”.

Towards the end of the song he realizes that it doesn’t really matter and he wants to sing what he feels like “so sing anything you feel like
and don’t let it get you down”.

body.plain: In “There’s No ‘I’ In Time”, Henry Tremain makes the argument that the existential realization that our lives have beginning and end should be liberating rather than frightening.

songs.lyrics:
[Verse 1]
Watching dust move
The dead skin, dancing was you
Now it’s something new
Awake in wait, floating away
In the wake of your own fate
Break under your dead weight
Or persuade change
What’s there to choose
Between nothing, nothing, there’s you
What have you to lose?

[Chorus]
Sing, once you die you were not alive
Terrify your lies
Fright out the zeitgeist
You are not, you weren’t, and you will not be
There’s no good times
When there’s no history

[Verse 2]
Why be obesely morbid?
Dread makes no sense, you were born dead
So live instead
Just admit it never happened
[Chorus]
Sing, once we die we were not alive
Terrify our lies
Fright out the zeitgeist
We are not, we weren’t, and we will not be
There’s no bad times
When there’s no historyEmbedShare URLCopyEmbedCopy

songs.full_title: In Praise of Idleness by TTNG
songs.title: In Praise of Idleness

description.plain: The title of this track comes from the collection http://www.zpub.com/notes/idle.html by Bertrand Russel. That piece is about the importance of having time to relax and enjoy life, especially among the lower classes. This song seems to take upon the role of a person who has been left behind in all the fun. Multiple references throughout this song show us the main character is committing self harm and attempting suicide, wishing the other people would just move on without them. In the end, the main character seems to stay alive to please the people in their lives, becoming the “true altruist” that they describe.

songs.title: Destroy The Tabernacle!

description.plain:
A song that touches on the subjects of Language Philosophy, which tries to relate logical arguments to language, and by doing so concludes about truth of statements in a language, whether or not a statement even can be  represented at all in a language, etc…

Bertrand Russel, who’s been referenced before in “In Praise Of Idleness” has researched Language Philosophy. In particular he formalized some parts that involve talking about things that do not exist.

Given the songs themes: misunderstanding one’s statements and skewing the truth, and past references to Russell, it is plausible that this was inspired by Russell’s “On Denoting”:

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On_Denoting

The title can also hint on a jab at religion texts being reinterpreted to the point of losing it’s meaning, to justify biases.

songs.full_title: In The Branches of Yggdrasil by TTNG
songs.title: In The Branches of Yggdrasil

description.plain:
Yggdrasil is an immense mythical tree that plays an important role in the Norse cosmology, because it connects the nine worlds.
The branches of Yggdrasil are so big that they stretch into the Heavens.

This instrumental interlude comes after the song “Left Aligned” which is about someone dying in a car crash. This makes it likely that these songs are connected with “Left Aligned” being from a friends perspective and “In the branches of Yggdrasil” being about the person dying going to heaven.

songs.title: Adventure, Stamina & Anger (Polished Version)

description.plain:
Bio by Audiotree on YouTube

“British math-rockers, TTNG, create a wall of sound that transcends their numbers. Tim Collis’ frantic tapping, finger picking, and Spanish stylings form the framework for their erratic blend of delicious notation. His tablature and chord progressions are so desirable that they’ve been made available for sale. Constant, extreme chord changes in odd tunings flow over dance-able beats. Ethereal vocals swoon over bold, echoing bass lines. The drum kit delivers rim shots, cymbal pings and driving floor toms galore while transforming their ever-evolving rhythm. They write like seasoned novelists, they perform with aplomb, they are TTNG.”
